This paper deals with the semantics of logic programming, which is a subfield of computer science that falls under several categories. The paper discusses the relationship between two approaches to characterizing different declarative semantics for logic programs with negation. This topic is relevant to several subcategories of computer science, including Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Databases (cs.DB), Programming Languages (cs.PL), and Software Engineering (cs.SE). However, since the paper focuses on the semantics of logic programming, cs.LO is the most likely category, followed by cs.AI and cs.DB. The paper also discusses the flexibility of the level mapping framework, which is relevant to cs.PL and cs.SE.
